objects.name: Goofy Guineapig HTTPS C2 (configured)
objects.description: Hardcoded HTTPS C2 URL and non-standard TLS port used by this sample (configuration string: HTTPS://static.tcplog.com:4443|HTTPS://static.tcplog.com:4443|12|5|1).

objects.name: Mutex generation algorithm
objects.description: Algorithm used by the backdoor to derive the mutex name to ensure single instance: four nested MD5 hashes of the computer name. (dynamic per-host mutex value).

objects.name: goofy guineapig
objects.description: Goofy Guineapig is a persistent Windows backdoor delivered as a UPX-packed, trojanised NSIS Firefox installer that sideloads a malicious DLL (Goopdate.dll) via a legitimate signed executable (GoogleUpdate.exe). It maintains persistence as a Windows service, implements multiple defense-evasion techniques (sandbox, timing, anti-debug, string obfuscation and UPX packing), supports multiple communications methods (HTTP, HTTPS on non-standard port 4443, UDP/KCP and raw sockets), embeds an RC4-encrypted payload/shellcode and can load plugins into-process or via process hollowing (dllhost.exe). It collects and exfiltrates system information (WMI and API-collected data), sends an obfuscated Authorization header in HTTP(S) C2 beacons, and performs file deletion to remove initial artifacts.

objects.name: Create or Modify System Process: Windows Service
objects.description: Goofy Guineapig maintains persistence as a Windows service.

objects.name: Masquerading: Match Legitimate Name or Location
objects.description: Goofy Guineapig masquerades as a FireFox installer and a Google updater.

objects.name: Virtualization/Sandbox Evasion: Time Based Evasion
objects.description: Goofy Guineapig checks the time register twice for a delay of more than 100 milliseconds and will not continue execution if more time has elapsed.

objects.name: Virtualization/Sandbox Evasion: System Checks
objects.description: Goofy Guineapig checks the disk size, physical memory size, and number of logical processors, and will not continue execution if any of the checks fail.

objects.name: Virtualization/Sandbox Evasion: User Activity Based Checks
objects.description: Goofy Guineapig checks for processes running on a system which indicate that it is being reverse engineered or debugged and will not continue execution if any of the checks fail (checks process names for 'dbg','debug','ida' and window titles).

objects.name: Obfuscated Files or Information: Software Packing
objects.description: Goofy Guineapig is UPX packed and packaged within a legitimate NSIS installer.

objects.name: Deobfuscate/Decode Files or Information
objects.description: Goofy Guineapig contains stack-based strings which are obfuscated with single byte XOR or subtraction throughout the binary; the shellcode/binary is also RC4 encrypted and must be decoded prior to execution.

objects.name: Hide Artifacts: Hidden Window
objects.description: Goofy Guineapig contains the functionality to perform process hollowing on dllhost.exe; when this is performed the process is created hidden.

objects.name: Indicator Removal on Host: File Deletion
objects.description: Goofy Guineapig initially runs in the download location, moves malicious files to a legitimate-looking ProgramData directory and deletes files from the initial download location (and the temp.bat self-deletes) to remove initial artifacts.

objects.name: Hijack Execution Flow: DLL Side-Loading
objects.description: A legitimate executable is installed by the Goofy Guineapig loader alongside a malicious DLL (Goopdate.dll) which will be loaded by the legitimate executable (side-loading).

objects.name: Process Injection: Process Hollowing
objects.description: Goofy Guineapig can perform process hollowing on the dllhost.exe binary, injecting content downloaded by the C2.

objects.name: System Binary Proxy Execution: Rundll32
objects.description: Goofy Guineapig persistence mechanism utilises rundll32.exe and url.dll to execute the legitimate binary which will load the malicious DLL.

objects.name: System Information Discovery
objects.description: Goofy Guineapig sends information about the infected machine in each C2 packet (operating system caption, antivirus product display name, adapters information, host and host name, computer name) to the C2, often as an obfuscated Authorization string in HTTP headers.

objects.name: Application Layer Protocol: Web Protocols
objects.description: Goofy Guineapig sends information to and receives tasking from C2 using HTTP(S) GET and POST requests; information about the victim is included in an obfuscated 'Authorization' header for HTTP-based communications.

objects.name: Fallback Channels
objects.description: Goofy Guineapig supports multiple communications methods (HTTPS, HTTP, UDP using KCP, and raw TCP sockets) and will select transport based on embedded configuration.

objects.name: Non-Standard Port
objects.description: Goofy Guineapig communicates over a non-standard HTTPS port (4443) for C2 communications.

objects.name: GoofyGuineapig_sessionstate
objects.description: YARA rule to detect related activity.
objects.pattern:
rule GoofyGuineapig_sessionstate
{
    meta:
        author = "NCSC"
        description = "Detects session state stack string setup in Goofy Guineapig."
        date = "2022-12-13"
        hash1 = "11b82826ec01aeec44e5e2504935b6aaccf51cac"

    strings:
        $1 = {66 C7 45 E8 44 69 66 C7 45 F2 65 64 C6 45 F1 74 66 C7 45 EB
63 6F C6 45 F4 00 C6 45 EA 73 C7 45 ED 6E 6E 65 63}
        $2 = {66 C7 45 ED 65 00 C7 45 E8 41 63 74 69 C6 45 EC 76 EB 2A}

    condition:
        uint16(0) == 0x5A4D and
        uint32(uint32(0x3c)) == 0x00004550 and
        all of them
}
